# Documentation Standards

## Source-of-truth map
| Question                                    | Go to                          |
|---------------------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| What should this feature do?                | `docs/PRD.md`                  |
| What columns does table X have?             | `SCHEMA.md`                    |
| Where does file Y live in the project?      | `ARCHITECTURE.md`              |
| Which component/colour for this UI pattern? | `.cursor/rules/theme.mdc`      |
| How does the ingestion cron work?           | `.cursor/rules/ingestion.mdc`  |
| What's the push notification abstraction?   | `.cursor/rules/flutter.mdc`    |
| What are the open product decisions?        | `docs/PRD.md` → Questions tracker |

## When to update SCHEMA.md
Immediately after every Supabase migration that adds, renames, or removes a column, table, enum
value, index, or RLS policy. Cursor reads `SCHEMA.md` as its authoritative column reference —
a stale schema file causes hallucinated column names in generated queries.

## When to update ARCHITECTURE.md
- Adding a new feature folder under `lib/src/features/`
- Adding or changing a route in `app_router.dart`
- Adding a new GitHub Actions workflow
- Changing the build flavor setup

## When to update README.md
- Completing a release milestone (update the "Status" badge and feature list)
- Adding a new build command or prerequisite
- Changing the Supabase setup steps

## When to update docs/PRD.md
- Closing an open decision in the Questions tracker
- Adding a feature to or removing one from a release phase
- Confirming the app name

## Files that do NOT need to be updated after every change
- `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` — update only when the convention itself changes, not on every implementation
- `LICENSE` — never changes
- `data/seed/internships_seed.json` — source data, not documentation

## Docs folder layout
```
docs/
  PRD.md                  # full product requirements document
```

## Style
- All documentation in Markdown.
- Tables preferred over bullet lists for structured comparisons.
- Code blocks for any code reference, command, or SQL.
- No stale TODOs — resolve or file an issue.
